00:01:48.790 --> 00:01:54.200
Hermitian operators, unitary
operators, [INAUDIBLE],

00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:57.740
matrix representations,
all kinds of things.

00:01:57.740 --> 00:02:02.120
That probably will be about two
weeks, three lectures at least.

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:05.940
So it will be a nice study.

00:02:05.940 --> 00:02:10.190
And in that way,
people that don't

00:02:10.190 --> 00:02:12.370
have a background
in linear algebra

00:02:12.370 --> 00:02:15.360
will feel more comfortable with
what we're going to be doing.

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:16.880
And I think even
for the people that

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:19.140
have a background
in linear algebra,

00:02:19.140 --> 00:02:22.470
you will gain a new
appreciation about the concepts

00:02:22.470 --> 00:02:23.950
that we meet here.

00:02:23.950 --> 00:02:28.790
So today, we begin, therefore,
with position and momentum,

00:02:28.790 --> 00:02:31.640
and these are operators
in quantum mechanics.

00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:36.260
And they have letters
to denote them. x,

00:02:36.260 --> 00:02:39.900
we put a hat with it,
that's a position operator.

00:02:39.900 --> 00:02:42.730
p, we put a hat on it.

00:02:42.730 --> 00:02:52.460
And the position and momentum
operators don't commute.

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:58.250
And the commutator
is given by ih bar.

00:02:58.250 --> 00:03:02.990
Now, we have been dealing
so far with wave functions.

00:03:02.990 --> 00:03:07.920
Our wave functions, where
these functions of x and t,

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:11.210
they represent the dynamics
of your system, the dynamics

00:03:11.210 --> 00:03:13.410
of your particle as
it moves in time.

00:03:13.410 --> 00:03:18.140
But time, as you are seeing
in quantum mechanics,

00:03:18.140 --> 00:03:19.602
is a little bit of a spectator.

00:03:19.602 --> 00:03:21.980
It's an arena where
things happen.

00:03:21.980 --> 00:03:25.670
But the operators, and most
of the interesting things,

00:03:25.670 --> 00:03:30.570
are going on without
reference to time.

00:03:30.570 --> 00:03:32.780
Time evolution, you
have an expansion

00:03:32.780 --> 00:03:35.140
of a wave function
in terms of energy,

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:38.340
eigenstates, at a given time.

00:03:38.340 --> 00:03:40.650
And then you can
evolve it easily

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:43.700
with the way we've
learned, adding e

00:03:43.700 --> 00:03:50.340
to the minus i et over h bar
for each energy eigenstate.

00:03:50.340 --> 00:03:52.710
So time will play no role here.

00:03:52.710 --> 00:03:55.380
So when I talk about the
wave function, at this moment

00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:57.630
you could put the
time, but we will

00:03:57.630 --> 00:04:01.400
talk about the wave functions
that have no time dependence.

00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:04.700
So, say, a psi of
x wave function.

00:04:11.010 --> 00:04:16.970
So this psi of x may be the true
wave function at time equals 0,

00:04:16.970 --> 00:04:23.510
or you could just simply
think of it as the psi of x.

00:04:23.510 --> 00:04:26.770
Now, this wave function
means that we're

00:04:26.770 --> 00:04:29.420
treating x in a
particular way, and we

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:33.310
say that we're working in the
x representation, the position

00:04:33.310 --> 00:04:35.570
representation.

00:04:35.570 --> 00:04:39.870
Now, this means that
we have an easy way

00:04:39.870 --> 00:04:43.800
to figure out what
this operator does

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:46.700
when it acts on this function.

00:04:46.700 --> 00:04:48.320
So what it acts
on this function,

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:50.840
it will give you
another function,

00:04:50.840 --> 00:04:53.730
and the definition of
this is that the position

00:04:53.730 --> 00:04:58.810
operator acting on
the function psi of x

00:04:58.810 --> 00:05:03.070
is defined to be
another function,

00:05:03.070 --> 00:05:06.845
which is the function
x times psi of x.

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:20.025
Well, we're talking about these
wave functions and operators

00:05:20.025 --> 00:05:21.380
on wave functions.

00:05:21.380 --> 00:05:25.550
And a recurrent theme
in quantum mechanics

00:05:25.550 --> 00:05:28.660
is that we will think
of wave functions,

00:05:28.660 --> 00:05:31.160
sometimes we call them states.

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:34.200
Sometimes we call them vectors.

00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:39.640
And we basically think of
wave functions as vectors.

00:05:39.640 --> 00:05:42.550
And things that act
on wave functions

00:05:42.550 --> 00:05:44.480
are the things that
act on vectors.

00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:46.390
And the things that
act on vectors,

00:05:46.390 --> 00:05:50.110
as you know in
mathematics, is matrices.

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:54.530
So we're compelled, even
at this early stage,

00:05:54.530 --> 00:05:57.600
to get a picture of
how that language would

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:02.410
go if we're talking
about these things.

00:06:02.410 --> 00:06:07.020
So how do we think of a
wave function as a vector?

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:12.000
And how do we think
of x as a matrix?

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:15.550
So there's a way to do that.

00:06:15.550 --> 00:06:21.580
It will not be totally
precise, but it's clear enough.

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:24.340
So suppose you have
a wave function,

00:06:24.340 --> 00:06:28.545
and we're interested in
its values from 0 up to a.

00:06:33.120 --> 00:06:38.230
This wave function is a
function of x between 0 and a.

00:06:38.230 --> 00:06:45.250
So it's the psi of x
for x between a and 0.

00:06:45.250 --> 00:06:47.420
That's all the information.

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:50.410
What we're going to
do is we're going

00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:55.540
to divide this thing,
this line, this segment,

00:06:55.540 --> 00:06:56.940
into a lot of pieces.

00:06:56.940 --> 00:06:58.610
And we're going to
say, look, instead

00:06:58.610 --> 00:07:03.040
of writing a function like
sine of x or cosine of x,

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:05.910
let's just give the
values and organize them

00:07:05.910 --> 00:07:09.780
as if this will be a
vector of many components.

00:07:09.780 --> 00:07:15.800
So let's divide this
in sizes epsilon,

00:07:15.800 --> 00:07:20.510
such that N times
epsilon is equal to a.

00:07:20.510 --> 00:07:23.700
So there are N of
these intervals.

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:29.696
So we think of psi as a
vector whose first component

00:07:29.696 --> 00:07:31.390
is psi at 0.

00:07:31.390 --> 00:07:34.190
The second is psi at epsilon.

00:07:34.190 --> 00:07:38.500
The third is psi at 2 epsilon.

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:43.560
And the last one is
psi at N epsilon.

00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:47.370
And depending on how much
accuracy you want to work with,

00:07:47.370 --> 00:07:54.390
you take epsilon smaller and
larger, keeping a constant.

00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:59.110
And this would be like
summarizing all the information

00:07:59.110 --> 00:08:00.705
of a function in a vector.

00:08:03.870 --> 00:08:08.800
Now, that's intuitively a
nice way to think of it.

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:13.960
May look, with your background
in classical physics,

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:18.910
a little strange that we
sort of put the value at 0

00:08:18.910 --> 00:08:22.740
along the x-axis, first
component, the value at epsilon

00:08:22.740 --> 00:08:26.260
along the y, the value
of 2 epsilon along the z.

00:08:26.260 --> 00:08:27.630
But we need more axes.

00:08:27.630 --> 00:08:30.270
So you need many axes here.

00:08:30.270 --> 00:08:39.299
In this case, this is a
N plus 1 column vector.

00:08:39.299 --> 00:08:43.480
It has N plus 1
entries, because 0 up

00:08:43.480 --> 00:08:45.740
to N, that's N plus 1 entries.

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:53.900
But that's a fine way
of thinking of it.

00:08:53.900 --> 00:08:56.700
Not exact because
we have an epsilon.

00:08:56.700 --> 00:09:00.020
In this way of thinking
about the wave function,

00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:08.110
we can then ask, what does
the matrix x hat look like?

00:09:08.110 --> 00:09:13.110
So x hat is an operator,
and it acts this way.

00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:15.650
So here is how it looks like.

00:09:15.650 --> 00:09:25.180
We would think of x hat as an
N plus 1 times N plus 1 matrix.

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:33.150
And its entries
are 0 everywhere,

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:35.190
except in the
diagonal, where they

00:09:35.190 --> 00:09:41.980
are 0 epsilon, 2
epsilon, up to N epsilon.

00:09:44.685 --> 00:09:47.265
And here is a big 0 and a big 0.

00:09:49.980 --> 00:09:55.700
This, I claim, is the way you
should think of the x operator

00:09:55.700 --> 00:10:01.640
if you thought of the wave
function the way we wrote it.

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:03.380
And how do we check that?

00:10:03.380 --> 00:10:09.500
Well, x operator acting on psi
should be this acting on that.

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:13.200
And then, indeed,
we see that if x hat

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:18.560
is acting on psi of
x, what do we get?

00:10:18.560 --> 00:10:25.350
Well, it's easy to multiply a
diagonal matrix times a vector.

00:10:25.350 --> 00:10:31.190
Here you get 0 times psi of 0.

00:10:31.190 --> 00:10:36.390
You get a vector, so let
me make this thinner.

00:10:36.390 --> 00:10:45.180
Then I get epsilon times psi
of epsilon, 2 epsilon times

00:10:45.180 --> 00:10:53.090
psi of 2 epsilon, up to N
epsilon times psi of N epsilon.

00:10:53.090 --> 00:10:58.490
And indeed, that matrix looks
like the matrix associated

00:10:58.490 --> 00:11:02.890
with this wave
function because here

00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:05.950
is the value at 0 of
this wave function.

00:11:05.950 --> 00:11:11.040
Here is the value at epsilon of
this wave function, and so on.

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:15.410
So this has worked
out all right.

00:11:15.410 --> 00:11:20.560
We can think of the wave
function as a column vector,

00:11:20.560 --> 00:11:24.540
and then the position operator
as this vector as well.

00:11:27.270 --> 00:11:32.670
Now, given that we know how
the x operator is defined,

00:11:32.670 --> 00:11:37.250
we can also think
easily about what

00:11:37.250 --> 00:11:40.810
is the expectation value
of x on a wave function.

00:11:40.810 --> 00:11:43.800
Something that you
really know, but now

00:11:43.800 --> 00:11:46.370
maybe becomes a little clearer.

00:11:46.370 --> 00:11:49.850
Here you're supposed
to do psi star

00:11:49.850 --> 00:11:56.590
of x times the x operator
acting on psi of x.

00:11:56.590 --> 00:11:59.220
But we have the
definition of this,

00:11:59.220 --> 00:12:05.040
so this is, as you imagine, dx--
and I should put primes maybe,

00:12:05.040 --> 00:12:09.430
well, I don't have to
put primes-- dx psi

00:12:09.430 --> 00:12:14.910
star of x x psi of
x, which is what

00:12:14.910 --> 00:12:16.575
you would have done anyway.

00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:26.200
Well, given that we've started
with this, we can ask also,

00:12:26.200 --> 00:12:29.960
is there eigenstates
of the x operator?

00:12:39.360 --> 00:12:40.970
Yes, there are.

00:12:40.970 --> 00:12:44.790
but then fortunately,
are a bit singular.

00:12:44.790 --> 00:12:48.150
So what should be
an eigenstate of x?

00:12:48.150 --> 00:12:51.860
It's some sort of state.

00:12:51.860 --> 00:12:55.480
Intuitively, it has a definite
value of the position.

00:12:55.480 --> 00:12:57.970
So it just exists
for some value of x.

00:12:57.970 --> 00:13:01.390
So it's naturally thought
as a delta function.

00:13:01.390 --> 00:13:09.370
So let me define a
function, psi sub x0 of x.

00:13:09.370 --> 00:13:13.530
So it's a function
of x labeled by x0,

00:13:13.530 --> 00:13:17.320
and define it to be
delta of x minus x0.

00:13:21.050 --> 00:13:24.790
So I claim that is an
eigenstate of x hat.

00:13:24.790 --> 00:13:31.750
x hat on psi x0 of x is
equal, by definition,

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:42.990
to x times psi x0 of x, which
is x times delta of x minus x0.

00:13:42.990 --> 00:13:45.220
And when you multiply
a function of x

00:13:45.220 --> 00:13:48.250
times a delta
function in x, it is

00:13:48.250 --> 00:13:50.660
possible to evaluate
the function that

00:13:50.660 --> 00:13:53.550
is being multiplied
by the delta function

00:13:53.550 --> 00:13:57.350
at the place where the
delta function fires.

00:13:57.350 --> 00:14:00.880
It has the same effect
on integrals or anything

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:01.730
that you would do.

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:08.230
So here, this is equal to
x0 times delta x minus x0.

00:14:08.230 --> 00:14:11.950
You evaluate the x at x0.

00:14:11.950 --> 00:14:18.550
And finally, this is x0 times
that function psi x0 of x.

00:14:18.550 --> 00:14:23.490
And therefore, you've shown
that this operator acting

00:14:23.490 --> 00:14:27.510
on this function reproduces
the function-- that's

00:14:27.510 --> 00:14:30.880
the definition of
eigenstate as an operator--

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:36.170
and the eigenvalue is the number
that appears here, and it's x0.

00:14:36.170 --> 00:14:44.150
So this function
is an eigenstate

00:14:44.150 --> 00:14:51.950
of x hat with
eigenvalue, e.v., x0.

00:14:59.010 --> 00:15:03.260
The only complication
with this eigenfunction

00:15:03.260 --> 00:15:05.780
is that it's not normalizable.

00:15:05.780 --> 00:15:09.060
So it doesn't
represent the particle.

00:15:09.060 --> 00:15:13.690
It can be used to
represent the particle,

00:15:13.690 --> 00:15:16.490
but it's a useful function.

00:15:16.490 --> 00:15:19.000
You can think of it
as something that

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:22.360
can help you do physics,
and don't insist

00:15:22.360 --> 00:15:26.000
that it represents a particle.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.640
So this is the
story for position.

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:32.680
And the position gets actually
more interesting as soon

00:15:32.680 --> 00:15:37.380
as you introduce the
dual quantity, momentum.

00:15:37.380 --> 00:15:40.660
So what is momentum here?

00:15:40.660 --> 00:15:55.020
So momentum is an operator, and
this operator must be defined.

00:15:55.020 --> 00:15:59.890
Now, you had a
shorthand for it in 804,

00:15:59.890 --> 00:16:04.790
which is p hat equal
h bar over i d dx.

00:16:08.070 --> 00:16:10.910
And this shorthand
means actually

00:16:10.910 --> 00:16:17.220
that, in what we call the
position representation where

00:16:17.220 --> 00:16:22.420
we're using wave functions
that depend on x, well,

00:16:22.420 --> 00:16:25.190
the momentum is given
by this operator.

00:16:25.190 --> 00:16:27.880
And the story of why
this was the case

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:30.150
was sort of something
that was elaborated

00:16:30.150 --> 00:16:33.870
on in 804, the work
of de Broglie, that

00:16:33.870 --> 00:16:38.430
saw that the
wavelength of the wave

00:16:38.430 --> 00:16:40.620
has to do with the
momentum of a wave.

00:16:40.620 --> 00:16:42.850
And finally, people
understood that this

00:16:42.850 --> 00:16:46.080
would measure the
momentum of the wave.

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:47.800
So this is the operator.

00:16:47.800 --> 00:16:51.570
And therefore, in the
representation that

00:16:51.570 --> 00:16:56.750
we're working-- representation
is a word that has a lot

00:16:56.750 --> 00:17:00.250
of precise meaning, but now
I'm just using it in the sense

00:17:00.250 --> 00:17:03.430
that, well, we're working
either with x's or with p's.

00:17:03.430 --> 00:17:05.140
And we're working with x's.

00:17:05.140 --> 00:17:09.440
That's why p looks like
something to do with x.

00:17:09.440 --> 00:17:13.369
So what is p hat
on a wave function?

00:17:13.369 --> 00:17:17.739
Well, that's what this means.

00:17:17.739 --> 00:17:20.119
It's another wave
function obtained

00:17:20.119 --> 00:17:23.990
by taking the x derivative.

00:17:23.990 --> 00:17:28.620
So that's the definition of
it acting on a wave function.

00:17:28.620 --> 00:17:33.310
The one thing that must
be verified, of course,

00:17:33.310 --> 00:17:38.340
is that this definition
is consistent or implies

00:17:38.340 --> 00:17:39.780
this commutation relation.

00:17:43.330 --> 00:17:46.840
So you've defined
it as an operator.

00:17:46.840 --> 00:17:49.770
x, we've defined
it as an operator.

00:17:49.770 --> 00:17:51.330
But most of us think
that it doesn't

00:17:51.330 --> 00:17:53.850
look like an operator
is multiplying.

00:17:53.850 --> 00:17:56.580
But it is an operator.

00:17:56.580 --> 00:17:59.230
So this one does look
like an operator.

00:17:59.230 --> 00:18:02.000
It's a differential operator.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:08.250
And you can try to see
if this equation is true.

00:18:08.250 --> 00:18:10.900
And the way to test
these commutators

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:13.110
is something that,
again, I don't think

00:18:13.110 --> 00:18:17.630
is unfamiliar to you,
but let's go through it,

00:18:17.630 --> 00:18:24.070
is that you try to evaluate
this product of operators

00:18:24.070 --> 00:18:27.510
acting on a wave function.

00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:32.400
And if things work
out well, we'll

00:18:32.400 --> 00:18:40.174
see you should get ih bar
times that wave function.

00:18:40.174 --> 00:18:43.090
If that is the case,
you say, OK, I've

00:18:43.090 --> 00:18:47.670
proven that equation, because
it's an operator equation.

00:18:47.670 --> 00:18:50.440
The left-hand side
of that equation

00:18:50.440 --> 00:18:53.510
is the product in different
orders of two operators,

00:18:53.510 --> 00:18:55.290
therefore it's an operator.

00:18:55.290 --> 00:18:57.710
The right-hand side
is another operator.

00:18:57.710 --> 00:19:02.270
It's the operator multiplied by
ih, anything that you'll get.

00:19:02.270 --> 00:19:07.530
Well, if this is an
operator identity,

00:19:07.530 --> 00:19:10.250
the operator on the left
must be equal to the operator

00:19:10.250 --> 00:19:14.440
on the right, which just means
that, acting on anything,

00:19:14.440 --> 00:19:16.080
they must give the same answer.

00:19:16.080 --> 00:19:20.000
So if I managed to prove
that this is equal to this,

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:24.550
I've proven that for
anything that is the answer.

00:19:24.550 --> 00:19:28.330
And therefore, I can
write the top one.

00:19:28.330 --> 00:19:31.890
And let me just do
it, even though this

00:19:31.890 --> 00:19:37.240
may be kind of familiar
to many of you.

00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:42.510
It's good to do this
slowly once in your life.

00:19:42.510 --> 00:19:44.800
So let's go through this.

00:19:44.800 --> 00:19:50.360
So this says x operator
p operator on psi

00:19:50.360 --> 00:19:54.840
minus p operator of
x operator on psi.

00:19:54.840 --> 00:20:01.460
When you have several operators,
like ABC acting on psi,

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:04.990
this really means
let C act on psi,

00:20:04.990 --> 00:20:11.960
and then let B act on C psi,
and then let A act on that.

00:20:11.960 --> 00:20:13.970
The operators act one by one.

00:20:13.970 --> 00:20:16.360
The closest one acts first.

00:20:16.360 --> 00:20:21.540
So here I'm supposed
to let B act on psi,

00:20:21.540 --> 00:20:23.160
but that means that thing.

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:30.180
So now x is acting
on h over i d psi dx.

00:20:32.750 --> 00:20:40.090
On this one, I have
p acting on x psi,

00:20:40.090 --> 00:20:43.900
because that's
what x hat psi is.

00:20:43.900 --> 00:20:47.770
Here, this is multiplication
by x of a function of x.

00:20:47.770 --> 00:20:52.120
So this is just h
over i x d psi dx.

00:20:55.310 --> 00:21:01.920
And here, I have h over i d
dx of this whole thing x psi.

00:21:04.950 --> 00:21:07.750
And you can see that
when you act here,

00:21:07.750 --> 00:21:12.080
you act first on the x,
and you get something.

00:21:12.080 --> 00:21:16.580
And then you act on the psi,
and you get this same term.

00:21:16.580 --> 00:21:24.130
So the only contribution
here is equal to minus h over

00:21:24.130 --> 00:21:28.330
i, the d dx on x
times psi, which

00:21:28.330 --> 00:21:32.530
is ih bar psi, which is
what I wanted to show.

00:21:36.050 --> 00:21:41.170
So this is true.

00:21:41.170 --> 00:21:44.880
And therefore, you could
say that this definition is

00:21:44.880 --> 00:21:47.800
consistent with your
definition of x,

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:51.710
and they represent
this operator.

00:21:51.710 --> 00:21:57.010
One more thing you could try
to do, and it's fun to do it,

00:21:57.010 --> 00:22:02.930
is we had a matrix
representation for x.

00:22:02.930 --> 00:22:05.353
Can I think of p as a matrix?

00:22:07.980 --> 00:22:09.180
How would you do it?

00:22:09.180 --> 00:22:11.880
What kind of matrix
would p look like?

00:22:15.680 --> 00:22:17.386
Well, yes?

00:22:17.386 --> 00:22:20.410
AUDIENCE: You just generate
a finite difference equation.

00:22:20.410 --> 00:22:22.620
PROFESSOR: You could
do it, exactly,

00:22:22.620 --> 00:22:25.920
with taking finite differences.

00:22:25.920 --> 00:22:28.590
So for example, if
you think that you

00:22:28.590 --> 00:22:35.555
want to produce the wave
function psi prime at 0,

00:22:35.555 --> 00:22:39.200
psi prime at epsilon,
psi prime, that's

00:22:39.200 --> 00:22:41.240
what the derivative
gives you, you'll

00:22:41.240 --> 00:22:47.970
write this as 1 over
epsilon, say, psi at epsilon

00:22:47.970 --> 00:22:50.040
minus psi at 0.

00:22:50.040 --> 00:22:53.950
That's the derivative
at 0 roughly.

00:22:53.950 --> 00:23:00.720
It would be psi at 2 epsilon
minus psi at 0 over 2.

00:23:00.720 --> 00:23:03.759
And you could build it.

00:23:03.759 --> 00:23:04.550
You could build it.

00:23:04.550 --> 00:23:05.600
I'm not going to do it.

00:23:05.600 --> 00:23:08.920
You may want to do
it and try and see

00:23:08.920 --> 00:23:13.550
how the derivative
operator looks as a matrix.

00:23:13.550 --> 00:23:18.100
And then if you really want
to spend some time thinking

00:23:18.100 --> 00:23:21.770
about it, you could try
to see if this matrix

00:23:21.770 --> 00:23:27.000
and this matrix commute
to give the right answer.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:28.800
And as you try it,
you will figure out

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:32.430
all kinds of funny
things that we

00:23:32.430 --> 00:23:34.580
will talk about
later in the course.

00:23:34.580 --> 00:23:39.010
So you can represent the
momentum operator as a matrix

00:23:39.010 --> 00:23:41.580
indeed, and there are
interesting things

00:23:41.580 --> 00:23:47.960
to say about it, and
it's a good subject.

00:23:47.960 --> 00:23:52.090
So let's continue
with the momentum

00:23:52.090 --> 00:23:55.380
and ask for eigenstates
of the momentum.

00:23:55.380 --> 00:24:06.796
So eigenstates of
p, you know them.

00:24:06.796 --> 00:24:09.250
They're e to the ipx things.

00:24:09.250 --> 00:24:13.650
So let's write them with some
convenient normalization.

00:24:16.180 --> 00:24:18.780
This is an [INAUDIBLE]
wave function

00:24:18.780 --> 00:24:21.880
that depends on x
with momentum p.

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:24.250
And we'll write it,
as a definition,

00:24:24.250 --> 00:24:32.000
as e to the ipx over h bar, and
I'll put it a 2 pi h bar here.

00:24:34.540 --> 00:24:38.440
It's kind of a
useful normalization.

00:24:38.440 --> 00:24:46.530
Then p hat on psi p of x,
well, p hat is supposed

00:24:46.530 --> 00:24:56.615
to take h over i d dx, and
take h over i d dx of psi p.

00:24:59.290 --> 00:25:03.330
And h over i cancels
the i over h.

00:25:03.330 --> 00:25:05.680
When you take the d
dx, you get p out,

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:07.520
and you get the
same wave function.

00:25:07.520 --> 00:25:12.590
So indeed, you get
p times psi p of x.

00:25:12.590 --> 00:25:19.010
So indeed, this is the
eigenstate of the momentum

00:25:19.010 --> 00:25:21.655
operator, and it has momentum p.

00:25:24.980 --> 00:25:28.150
Well, what is the use of this?

00:25:28.150 --> 00:25:33.370
Well, say you have a
representation, what

00:25:33.370 --> 00:25:36.180
we call the position
representation,

00:25:36.180 --> 00:25:38.880
of the wave function
and operators.

00:25:38.880 --> 00:25:42.450
Let us think now of the
momentum representation.

00:25:42.450 --> 00:25:45.200
So what does all that mean?

00:25:45.200 --> 00:25:49.760
Well, there is the Fourier
transform operation

00:25:49.760 --> 00:25:54.780
in which we have psi of p.

00:25:54.780 --> 00:26:00.780
Well, let me write it
this way, actually.

00:26:00.780 --> 00:26:05.930
I'll write any psi
of x physically

00:26:05.930 --> 00:26:11.340
can be represented as a sum
of momentum eigenstates.

00:26:11.340 --> 00:26:15.040
Therefore, that's
Fourier's theorem,

00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:23.600
minus infinity to infinity
dp e to the ipx over h bar

00:26:23.600 --> 00:26:29.060
square root of 2 pi
h psi tilde of p.

00:26:31.880 --> 00:26:38.870
That's Fourier transformation,
defines psi tilde of p.

00:26:38.870 --> 00:26:44.450
And Fourier's theorem is
the fact that not only you

00:26:44.450 --> 00:26:49.020
can do that, but you can invert
it so that psi tilde of p

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:52.935
can also be written as an
integral, this time over x

00:26:52.935 --> 00:27:00.620
from minus infinity to infinity
e to the minus ipx over h

00:27:00.620 --> 00:27:09.190
bar, also 2 pi h bar psi of x.

00:27:09.190 --> 00:27:12.690
So let's ponder this equation
for a couple of minutes.

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:21.820
Well, as a physicist,
you think of this, well,

00:27:21.820 --> 00:27:25.910
this is telling me that
any wave function could

00:27:25.910 --> 00:27:30.380
be written as a superposition
of momentum eigenstates.

00:27:30.380 --> 00:27:33.050
Here are the
momentum eigenstates.

00:27:33.050 --> 00:27:35.140
And for each value
of momentum, you

00:27:35.140 --> 00:27:39.040
have some coefficient here
that tells me how much of that

00:27:39.040 --> 00:27:40.640
momentum eigenstate I have.

00:27:44.340 --> 00:27:46.600
Now, here is the opposite one.

00:27:46.600 --> 00:27:52.050
Psi tilde of p and psi of
x are related in this way.

00:27:52.050 --> 00:27:55.340
So these coefficients, if
you want to calculate them,

00:27:55.340 --> 00:27:57.900
you calculate them this way.

00:27:57.900 --> 00:28:03.100
But now let's think of it as
a change of representation.

00:28:06.810 --> 00:28:10.210
The physics is
contained in psi of x.

00:28:10.210 --> 00:28:15.060
All what you wish to know about
this physical system in quantum

00:28:15.060 --> 00:28:18.040
mechanics is there in psi of x.

00:28:18.040 --> 00:28:21.600
But it's also there in
psi of p, because they

00:28:21.600 --> 00:28:24.270
contain the same information.

00:28:24.270 --> 00:28:28.370
So there are different ways of
encoding the same information.

00:28:31.540 --> 00:28:36.150
What is the relation
between them?

00:28:36.150 --> 00:28:39.240
This, we thought
of it as a vector,

00:28:39.240 --> 00:28:44.210
vector in position space, an
infinite dimensional space

00:28:44.210 --> 00:28:46.880
that is talking about positions.

00:28:46.880 --> 00:28:51.580
This is another vector
in momentum space.

00:28:51.580 --> 00:28:53.720
Think of it now
the infinite line.

00:28:53.720 --> 00:28:58.390
So this is an infinite vector
with all those points little

00:28:58.390 --> 00:29:02.030
by little, from minus infinity
to plus infinity, all of them

00:29:02.030 --> 00:29:05.300
there, gigantic vector.

00:29:05.300 --> 00:29:08.410
And here is another
gigantic vector with p

00:29:08.410 --> 00:29:11.250
from minus infinity to infinity.

00:29:11.250 --> 00:29:13.420
And in between,
there's an integral.

00:29:13.420 --> 00:29:17.530
But now, with your picture
of quantum mechanics,

00:29:17.530 --> 00:29:21.740
you see an integral, but
you also see a matrix.

00:29:21.740 --> 00:29:23.580
And what is this matrix?

00:29:23.580 --> 00:29:28.650
Think of this as some
sort of psi sub p.

00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:38.590
And this as some
sort of matrix, px

00:29:38.590 --> 00:29:47.020
psi x, in which if you have a
product-- you'll remember when

00:29:47.020 --> 00:29:51.230
you multiply matrices,
a matrix on a vector,

00:29:51.230 --> 00:29:54.520
you sum over the second index.

00:29:54.520 --> 00:29:56.360
That's the product for matrix.

00:29:56.360 --> 00:29:59.400
And then the first
index is the index here.

00:29:59.400 --> 00:30:04.330
So here is what it,
more or less, is like.

00:30:04.330 --> 00:30:07.040
Psi tilde of p
[? subtend ?] by this,

00:30:07.040 --> 00:30:11.750
and this matrix depends on two
labels, p and x, and it's that.

00:30:11.750 --> 00:30:16.340
So it's a matrix full of phases.

00:30:16.340 --> 00:30:20.020
So how do you pass from the
coordinate representation

00:30:20.020 --> 00:30:23.490
of the information, a vector
of all values of the wave

00:30:23.490 --> 00:30:25.340
function in all positions?

00:30:25.340 --> 00:30:31.140
By multiplying with this
matrix of phases that is here,

00:30:31.140 --> 00:30:33.070
and it gives you
this representation.

00:30:33.070 --> 00:30:38.670
So different representations
means using different vectors

00:30:38.670 --> 00:30:42.140
to represent the physics.

00:30:42.140 --> 00:30:45.610
And this vector is
a very nice one.

00:30:45.610 --> 00:30:49.070
And because of these properties
of the momentum operator

00:30:49.070 --> 00:30:52.940
and all these things, this
vector is also a very nice one.

00:30:52.940 --> 00:30:55.690
And there's an
integral transform

00:30:55.690 --> 00:30:59.480
or some sort of infinite matrix
product that relates them.

00:31:02.450 --> 00:31:05.700
And we shouldn't be
uncomfortable about it.

00:31:05.700 --> 00:31:07.260
That's all fine.

00:31:07.260 --> 00:31:12.190
So we say that we
have, for example,

00:31:12.190 --> 00:31:22.260
psi of x as one representation
of the state and psi tilde of p

00:31:22.260 --> 00:31:25.635
as another representation
of the same physics.

00:31:30.950 --> 00:31:38.780
We can do one more thing
here, If I continue.

00:31:38.780 --> 00:31:46.160
We can take that boxed equation
on the blackboard up there

00:31:46.160 --> 00:31:54.430
and act with h bar over
i d dx on psi of x.

00:31:57.120 --> 00:32:02.160
So that is equal to
h i d dx, and I'll

00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:08.070
write what psi of x is, is
minus infinity to infinity dp e

00:32:08.070 --> 00:32:12.680
to the ipx over
h bar square root

00:32:12.680 --> 00:32:17.950
of 2 pi h bar psi tilde of p.

00:32:22.580 --> 00:32:28.190
Now, when we act on this, as
you know, h bar over i d dx

00:32:28.190 --> 00:32:32.020
just acts on this and
produces the factor of p.

00:32:32.020 --> 00:32:38.410
So this is equal to minus
infinity to infinity dp e

00:32:38.410 --> 00:32:45.890
to the ipx over h bar over
square root of 2 pi h bar p

00:32:45.890 --> 00:32:48.140
times psi tilde of p.

00:32:54.720 --> 00:32:59.240
So look at this equation again.

00:32:59.240 --> 00:33:02.940
This double arrow is
to mean that there

00:33:02.940 --> 00:33:05.080
are equivalent physics in them.

00:33:05.080 --> 00:33:06.790
They have the same information.

00:33:06.790 --> 00:33:10.300
It's the same data encoded
in a different way.

00:33:10.300 --> 00:33:13.329
And that different
way, this arrow

00:33:13.329 --> 00:33:14.412
is Fourier transformation.

00:33:17.420 --> 00:33:20.750
And this Fourier transformation
is explained here.

00:33:20.750 --> 00:33:26.920
So now you have Fourier
transformation the same way.

00:33:26.920 --> 00:33:30.270
So here we have--
what we've learned

00:33:30.270 --> 00:33:41.120
is that h over i d dx of psi is
represented in momentum space

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:47.060
by p psi tilde of p.

00:33:47.060 --> 00:33:52.620
And this was p hat
acting on psi of x.

00:33:55.520 --> 00:34:00.900
So the corresponding thing
in momentum space of p hat

00:34:00.900 --> 00:34:08.530
acting on psi of x is p
multiplying psi tilde of p,

00:34:08.530 --> 00:34:15.590
which is to say that we can
think of the abstract operator

00:34:15.590 --> 00:34:25.620
p hat acting on psi tilde of
p as just p psi tilde of p.

00:34:33.040 --> 00:34:39.639
So in momentum space,
the operator p hat

00:34:39.639 --> 00:34:41.260
acts in a very easy way.

00:34:44.280 --> 00:34:48.300
In coordinate space,
it takes derivatives.

00:34:48.300 --> 00:34:51.940
In momentum space,
it's multiplicative.

00:34:51.940 --> 00:34:58.620
So in position space,
x is multiplicative.

00:34:58.620 --> 00:35:05.380
But in momentum space, x
would not be multiplicative.

00:35:05.380 --> 00:35:07.780
x would also be a derivative.

00:35:07.780 --> 00:35:11.870
So I leave it for
you as an exercise

00:35:11.870 --> 00:35:19.540
to show that or convince
yourself in several ways,

00:35:19.540 --> 00:35:34.270
that x hat is really i h bar d
dp in p space, in i h bar d dp.

00:35:36.960 --> 00:35:37.760
All right.

00:35:37.760 --> 00:35:43.590
So that's really all I wanted to
say about position and momentum

00:35:43.590 --> 00:35:45.850
operators at this moment.

00:35:45.850 --> 00:35:49.960
They will come back when we'll
introduce bra-ket notation

00:35:49.960 --> 00:35:50.460
in detail.

00:35:50.460 --> 00:35:52.550
We'll revisit this a little.

00:35:52.550 --> 00:35:56.690
But the main concepts
have been illustrated.

00:35:56.690 --> 00:35:57.980
Are there questions?

00:35:57.980 --> 00:36:01.330
We're about to leave
this, so if you

00:36:01.330 --> 00:36:02.750
have any questions
at this moment.

00:36:02.750 --> 00:36:03.310
Yes?

00:36:03.310 --> 00:36:04.795
AUDIENCE: Could
you explain again

00:36:04.795 --> 00:36:10.240
how you used this
[INAUDIBLE] h bar over i d dx

00:36:10.240 --> 00:36:12.730
assign to [INAUDIBLE]?

00:36:12.730 --> 00:36:13.920
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:36:13.920 --> 00:36:18.760
So the question was, why did
I associate these things?

00:36:18.760 --> 00:36:24.340
So it really goes back here to
what the meaning of this arrow

00:36:24.340 --> 00:36:25.420
is.

00:36:25.420 --> 00:36:28.510
The meaning of this arrow
is Fourier transformation.

00:36:28.510 --> 00:36:34.420
So this psi tilde and psi of
x are related in this way.

00:36:34.420 --> 00:36:36.540
That's Fourier
transformation, and that's

00:36:36.540 --> 00:36:38.850
what we mean by this arrow.

00:36:38.850 --> 00:36:43.950
It also means that whatever
physics you have here,

00:36:43.950 --> 00:36:45.760
you have it there.

00:36:45.760 --> 00:36:52.570
So really, when you have
something acting on a state,

00:36:52.570 --> 00:36:56.050
for example, if you have some
operator acting in here, well,

00:36:56.050 --> 00:36:58.270
you get a new wave function.

00:36:58.270 --> 00:37:00.410
And there should be
one on the right that

00:37:00.410 --> 00:37:03.810
corresponds to it, that has
the same information as the one

00:37:03.810 --> 00:37:06.030
in which you've
acted with something.

00:37:06.030 --> 00:37:10.330
So what we claim here is that,
also in the sense of Fourier

00:37:10.330 --> 00:37:15.420
transformation or having the
same information, h bar over i,

00:37:15.420 --> 00:37:20.130
the derivative of psi,
is encoded by this.

00:37:20.130 --> 00:37:24.660
So we say, thinking
abstractly, what is this?

00:37:24.660 --> 00:37:28.970
This is the momentum operator.

00:37:28.970 --> 00:37:35.350
Therefore, I'm going to say that
the momentum operator really

00:37:35.350 --> 00:37:39.000
is the same momentum
operator, whether it acts

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:42.810
on wave functions that you show
them to mean this way or wave

00:37:42.810 --> 00:37:45.680
functions that, because
you're in another mood,

00:37:45.680 --> 00:37:48.660
you decide to give them
to me in momentum space.

00:37:48.660 --> 00:37:53.690
So as you change your mood, the
operator takes different forms

00:37:53.690 --> 00:37:56.380
but is doing the same thing.

00:37:56.380 --> 00:37:58.030
It's totally reversible.

00:37:58.030 --> 00:38:02.460
It's acting on that-- you
see, the operator is always

00:38:02.460 --> 00:38:06.370
the same, but you give me the
data in two different ways,

00:38:06.370 --> 00:38:10.170
then the operator has to do
the thing in a different way.

00:38:10.170 --> 00:38:12.770
So that's what it means
that the operator has

00:38:12.770 --> 00:38:15.030
different representations.

00:38:15.030 --> 00:38:16.770
In the [INAUDIBLE]
representation,

00:38:16.770 --> 00:38:18.790
it looks like a derivative.

00:38:18.790 --> 00:38:21.915
In the momentum representation,
it looks like multiplying.

00:38:25.130 --> 00:38:27.828
Other questions?

00:38:27.828 --> 00:38:28.806
Yes?

