01:01:59.420 --> 01:02:00.310
All right.

01:02:00.310 --> 01:02:03.060
Who votes up?

01:02:03.060 --> 01:02:03.560
Nobody.

01:02:03.560 --> 01:02:05.503
Who votes down?

01:02:05.503 --> 01:02:06.405
Yeah, [INAUDIBLE].

01:02:06.405 --> 01:02:08.640
Down, exactly.

01:02:08.640 --> 01:02:10.150
How do you see down?

01:02:10.150 --> 01:02:14.250
Well, one way to see this,
look at the cross-section.

01:02:14.250 --> 01:02:18.980
You would have this
wire here like that.

01:02:18.980 --> 01:02:22.870
The current is coming in on this
side and going out this way.

01:02:22.870 --> 01:02:26.470
Here you have the field lines
that go through those two

01:02:26.470 --> 01:02:33.570
edges, and the magnetic
field is like that.

01:02:33.570 --> 01:02:38.550
And the force goes like I cross
B. So I goes in, B goes out.

01:02:38.550 --> 01:02:42.720
The force must be like
that, a little bit of force.

01:02:42.720 --> 01:02:46.700
In this one, I cross
B would be like that,

01:02:46.700 --> 01:02:48.160
a little bit of force.

01:02:48.160 --> 01:02:49.070
Yep.

01:02:49.070 --> 01:02:52.105
Has a component down because
the field lines are diverging.

01:02:56.080 --> 01:02:59.920
So what is the force
really given by?

01:02:59.920 --> 01:03:05.540
The force is given
by the gradient

01:03:05.540 --> 01:03:14.490
of mu dot B. This is derived in
E&amp;M. I will not derive it here.

01:03:14.490 --> 01:03:17.490
This is not really the
point of this course.

01:03:17.490 --> 01:03:21.310
But you can see that
it's consistent.

01:03:21.310 --> 01:03:26.080
This is saying that the force
goes in the direction that

01:03:26.080 --> 01:03:29.810
makes mu dot B grow the fastest.

01:03:29.810 --> 01:03:34.830
Now mu, in this case, is up.

01:03:34.830 --> 01:03:40.170
So mu dot B is positive, because
mu and the magnetic field

01:03:40.170 --> 01:03:41.550
go in the same direction.

01:03:41.550 --> 01:03:43.610
So mu dot b is positive.

01:03:43.610 --> 01:03:47.720
So the force will be towards
the direction-- that's

01:03:47.720 --> 01:03:51.220
what the gradient is--
that this becomes bigger.

01:03:51.220 --> 01:03:55.210
So it becomes bigger here,
because as the field lines come

01:03:55.210 --> 01:03:58.570
together, that means
stronger magnetic field.

01:03:58.570 --> 01:04:03.550
And therefore, mu dot B would be
larger, so it's pointing down.

01:04:03.550 --> 01:04:07.790
If you have a magnetic
field that is roughly

01:04:07.790 --> 01:04:11.010
in the z direction, there
will be a simplification,

01:04:11.010 --> 01:04:13.020
as we will see very soon.

01:04:13.020 --> 01:04:16.480
So what did Stern
and Gerlach do?

01:04:16.480 --> 01:04:21.110
Well, they were working
with silver atoms.

01:04:21.110 --> 01:04:25.410
And silver atoms
have 47 electrons,

01:04:25.410 --> 01:04:30.070
out of which 46 fill up
the levels and equal 1,

01:04:30.070 --> 01:04:33.620
2, 3, and 4.

01:04:33.620 --> 01:04:41.010
Just one lone electron, a 5s
electron, the 47th electron,

01:04:41.010 --> 01:04:45.810
it's a lonely electron that
is out in a spherical shell,

01:04:45.810 --> 01:04:49.760
we know now with zero
orbital angular momentum.

01:04:49.760 --> 01:04:52.130
It's an S state.

01:04:52.130 --> 01:04:58.110
And therefore, throwing silver
atoms through your apparatus

01:04:58.110 --> 01:05:03.320
was pretty much the same
thing as throwing electrons,

01:05:03.320 --> 01:05:05.810
because all these
other electrons

01:05:05.810 --> 01:05:08.440
are tied up with each other.

01:05:08.440 --> 01:05:11.970
We know now one has
spin up, one spin down.

01:05:11.970 --> 01:05:15.710
Nothing contributes, no
angular momentum as a whole.

01:05:15.710 --> 01:05:19.090
And then you have this
last electron unpaired.

01:05:19.090 --> 01:05:21.060
It has a spin.

01:05:21.060 --> 01:05:23.066
So it's like throwing spins.

01:05:26.130 --> 01:05:32.820
So moreover, throwing spins,
as far as we're concerned,

01:05:32.820 --> 01:05:34.510
Stern and Gerlach wouldn't care.

01:05:34.510 --> 01:05:39.370
Because of these relations,
it's throwing in dipole moments.

01:05:39.370 --> 01:05:42.910
And they would care about
that because magnetic fields

01:05:42.910 --> 01:05:46.740
push dipole moments up or down.

01:05:46.740 --> 01:05:52.690
Therefore, what is the
apparatus these people had?

01:05:52.690 --> 01:06:01.760
It was sort of like
this, with an oven,

01:06:01.760 --> 01:06:04.580
and you produce
some silver atoms

01:06:04.580 --> 01:06:10.450
that come out as a gas,
a collimating slit.

01:06:14.490 --> 01:06:19.490
Then you put axes
here-- we put axes just

01:06:19.490 --> 01:06:22.060
to know the components
we're talking about.

01:06:22.060 --> 01:06:39.850
And then there's magnets,
some sort of magnet like this,

01:06:39.850 --> 01:06:41.780
and the screen over there.

01:06:45.320 --> 01:06:49.285
So basically, this
form of this magnet

01:06:49.285 --> 01:06:53.330
that I've tried to draw there,
although it's not so easy, if I

01:06:53.330 --> 01:06:56.945
would take a cross-section
it would look like this.

01:07:01.740 --> 01:07:03.866
So the magnetic
field has a gradient.

01:07:06.430 --> 01:07:09.330
The lines bend a bit,
so there's a gradient

01:07:09.330 --> 01:07:10.445
of the magnetic field.

01:07:10.445 --> 01:07:16.870
And it's mostly in the z
direction, so z direction

01:07:16.870 --> 01:07:18.280
being pointed out here.

01:07:18.280 --> 01:07:19.590
So there's the magnetic field.

01:07:19.590 --> 01:07:21.800
The beam then comes here.

01:07:21.800 --> 01:07:24.045
And the question is, what
do you get on this screen?

01:07:27.570 --> 01:07:33.278
Now, I have it a little too low.

01:07:33.278 --> 01:07:37.110
The beam comes there
and goes through there.

01:07:37.110 --> 01:07:41.840
So the analysis that
we would have to do

01:07:41.840 --> 01:07:47.100
is basically an
analysis of the forces.

01:07:47.100 --> 01:07:52.020
And relatively, we
don't care too much.

01:07:52.020 --> 01:07:55.870
The fact is that
there's basically,

01:07:55.870 --> 01:07:59.190
because the magnetic field
is mostly in the z direction

01:07:59.190 --> 01:08:01.570
and varies in z
direction, there will

01:08:01.570 --> 01:08:04.940
be a force basically
in the z direction.

01:08:04.940 --> 01:08:05.790
Why is that?

01:08:05.790 --> 01:08:07.720
Because you take
this, and you say,

01:08:07.720 --> 01:08:15.870
well, that's roughly mu
z Bz, because it's mostly

01:08:15.870 --> 01:08:18.120
a magnetic field
in the z direction.

01:08:18.120 --> 01:08:24.670
And mu is a constant, so it's
basically gradient of Bz.

01:08:24.670 --> 01:08:26.029
Now, that's a vector.

01:08:26.029 --> 01:08:30.160
But we're saying also
most of the gradient of Bz

01:08:30.160 --> 01:08:37.109
is in the z direction,
so it's basically dBz dz.

01:08:45.569 --> 01:08:47.830
Now, there is some
bending of the lines,

01:08:47.830 --> 01:08:50.750
so there's a little bit of
gradient in other directions.

01:08:50.750 --> 01:08:54.220
But people have gone
through the analysis,

01:08:54.220 --> 01:08:57.790
and they don't matter for
any calculation that you do.

01:08:57.790 --> 01:09:00.830
They actually average out.

01:09:00.830 --> 01:09:04.850
So roughly, this gradient
is in the z direction.

01:09:04.850 --> 01:09:09.040
I'm sorry, the gradient is
supposed to be a vector.

01:09:09.040 --> 01:09:11.600
So you get a force
in the z direction.

01:09:11.600 --> 01:09:16.350
And therefore, the thing
that people expected

01:09:16.350 --> 01:09:17.870
was the following.

01:09:17.870 --> 01:09:24.200
You know, here comes one atom,
and it has its magnetic moment.

01:09:24.200 --> 01:09:28.420
Well, they've all been boiling
in this oven for a while.

01:09:28.420 --> 01:09:29.740
They're very disordered.

01:09:29.740 --> 01:09:33.055
Some have a z component of
magnetic-- the magnetic moment

01:09:33.055 --> 01:09:37.029
is pointing like that, so they
have some component, some down.

01:09:37.029 --> 01:09:37.880
Some are here.

01:09:37.880 --> 01:09:39.569
They have no component.

01:09:39.569 --> 01:09:44.260
It's all Boltzmann distributed
all over the directions.

01:09:44.260 --> 01:09:49.870
Therefore, you're going
to get a smudge like this.

01:09:49.870 --> 01:09:53.240
Some ones are going to be
deflected a lot because they

01:09:53.240 --> 01:09:57.030
have lots of z
component of angular

01:09:57.030 --> 01:10:00.240
momentum or z magnetic moment.

01:10:00.240 --> 01:10:04.720
Others are going to
be deflected little.

01:10:04.720 --> 01:10:07.590
So this was the
classical expectation.

01:10:07.590 --> 01:10:11.080
And the shock was that
you got, actually,

01:10:11.080 --> 01:10:16.010
one peak here, an empty
space, and another peak there.

01:10:16.010 --> 01:10:17.950
That was called
space quantization.

01:10:22.720 --> 01:10:26.790
Stern and Gerlach worked
with a magnetic field

01:10:26.790 --> 01:10:35.190
that was of about 0.1
tesla, a tenth of a tesla.

01:10:35.190 --> 01:10:38.600
And in their experiment,
the space quantization,

01:10:38.600 --> 01:10:42.680
this difference, was
1/5 of a millimeter.

01:10:45.740 --> 01:10:51.110
So not that big, but
it was a clear thing.

01:10:51.110 --> 01:10:53.700
It was there.

01:10:53.700 --> 01:11:00.350
So everybody was confused.

01:11:00.350 --> 01:11:04.340
They thought it was the orbital
spin, angular momentum that

01:11:04.340 --> 01:11:06.600
somehow had been measured.

01:11:06.600 --> 01:11:08.880
At the end of the
day, that was wrong.

01:11:08.880 --> 01:11:10.370
It couldn't have been that.

01:11:10.370 --> 01:11:13.400
People understood the Bohr
atom, realized, no, there's

01:11:13.400 --> 01:11:15.220
no angular momentum there.

01:11:15.220 --> 01:11:17.810
The idea of the spin
came back, and you

01:11:17.810 --> 01:11:20.820
would have to do a
calculation to determine

01:11:20.820 --> 01:11:23.030
what is the value of the spin.

01:11:23.030 --> 01:11:28.960
So the exact factor took
a while to get it right.

01:11:28.960 --> 01:11:36.660
But with the idea that mu z is
equal to minus 2 Bohr magenton

01:11:36.660 --> 01:11:39.250
Sz over h bar, which
we wrote before.

01:11:42.330 --> 01:11:46.900
Well, mu z, if you
know the strength

01:11:46.900 --> 01:11:51.350
of your magnetic field, you
can calculate the deflections.

01:11:51.350 --> 01:11:53.030
You know what mu B is.

01:11:53.030 --> 01:11:57.040
So therefore, you get
the value for Sz over h.

01:11:57.040 --> 01:12:00.540
And experiments
suggested that Sz over h

01:12:00.540 --> 01:12:04.165
was either plus or minus 1/2.

01:12:08.000 --> 01:12:15.280
And this kind of particle, it
has Sz over h bar equal plus

01:12:15.280 --> 01:12:20.970
or minus 1/2, is called
the spin-1/2 particle.

01:12:20.970 --> 01:12:26.400
So again, from this equation,
this can be measured.

01:12:29.930 --> 01:12:34.725
And you then use this,
and you get this value.

01:12:39.800 --> 01:12:43.160
So the experiment is
a little confusing.

01:12:43.160 --> 01:12:44.760
Why did this happen?

01:12:44.760 --> 01:12:48.020
And how do we think of
it quantum mechanically?

01:12:48.020 --> 01:12:53.340
Now 804 sort of began
with these kind of things.

01:12:53.340 --> 01:12:56.680
And you know by now
that what's happening

01:12:56.680 --> 01:13:01.090
is the following, that somehow,
mathematically, every state is

01:13:01.090 --> 01:13:04.000
a superposition of a
spin up and a spin down.

01:13:04.000 --> 01:13:06.410
So every particle
that goes there

01:13:06.410 --> 01:13:10.230
has half of its brain in the
spin up and half of its brain

01:13:10.230 --> 01:13:11.630
in the spin down.

01:13:11.630 --> 01:13:14.170
And then as it goes
through the magnetic field,

01:13:14.170 --> 01:13:17.990
this thing splits, but each
particle is in both beams

01:13:17.990 --> 01:13:19.880
still.

01:13:19.880 --> 01:13:22.140
And they just have
this dual existence

01:13:22.140 --> 01:13:25.130
until there's a screen
and there's detectors.

01:13:25.130 --> 01:13:27.460
So they have to decide
what happens, and then

01:13:27.460 --> 01:13:33.260
either collapses in the
top beam or lower beam.

01:13:33.260 --> 01:13:35.630
Nothing happens until
you put the screen.

01:13:35.630 --> 01:13:38.790
That's what we think now
is the interpretation

01:13:38.790 --> 01:13:39.980
of this experiment.

01:13:39.980 --> 01:13:43.720
But let's use the
last few minutes

01:13:43.720 --> 01:13:50.440
to just write this in terms of
boxes and get the right ideas.

01:13:50.440 --> 01:13:57.590
So instead of drawing
all that stuff,

01:13:57.590 --> 01:14:01.620
we'll draw a little
box called a z hat

01:14:01.620 --> 01:14:04.690
box, a Stern-Gerlach apparatus.

01:14:04.690 --> 01:14:10.350
In comes a beam, out
would come two beams,

01:14:10.350 --> 01:14:17.150
Sz equal h bar over 2 and
Sz equal minus h bar over 2.

01:14:17.150 --> 01:14:19.980
And the convention is
that the plus goes up

01:14:19.980 --> 01:14:21.840
and the minus goes
down, which I think

01:14:21.840 --> 01:14:24.555
is probably consistent
with that drawing.

01:14:27.470 --> 01:14:29.980
And that's the
Stern-Gerlach apparatus.

01:14:29.980 --> 01:14:34.150
It measures Sz, and
it splits the beam.

01:14:34.150 --> 01:14:36.510
Each particle goes
into both beams

01:14:36.510 --> 01:14:38.520
until there's a
device that measures

01:14:38.520 --> 01:14:41.270
and decides where you go.

01:14:41.270 --> 01:14:44.440
So you can do the
following arrangements.

01:14:44.440 --> 01:14:50.590
So here's arrangement number 1,
a Stern-Gerlach device with z.

01:14:50.590 --> 01:14:54.000
Then you block the
lower one and let

01:14:54.000 --> 01:15:03.650
the top one go as Sz
equal h bar over 2.

01:15:03.650 --> 01:15:08.710
And then you put another
Stern-Gerlach machine, z hat,

01:15:08.710 --> 01:15:12.220
that has two outputs.

01:15:12.220 --> 01:15:15.270
And then you ask,
what's going to happen?

01:15:15.270 --> 01:15:19.680
And the experiment can be
done and, actually, there's

01:15:19.680 --> 01:15:23.720
nothing here coming out, and
all the particles come out here

01:15:23.720 --> 01:15:26.250
with Sz equal h bar over 2.

01:15:30.230 --> 01:15:34.280
What are we going
to learn from this?

01:15:34.280 --> 01:15:36.710
In our picture of
quantum mechanics,

01:15:36.710 --> 01:15:39.450
we're going to think
of this as there

01:15:39.450 --> 01:15:43.700
are states of the
electron that have--

01:15:43.700 --> 01:15:46.610
and I will write
them with respect

01:15:46.610 --> 01:15:51.950
to z-- they have
plus h bar over 2

01:15:51.950 --> 01:15:58.060
and states that have
minus h bar over 2.

01:15:58.060 --> 01:16:03.590
And what we will think is that
these are really old basis

01:16:03.590 --> 01:16:09.080
states, that any other state,
even one that points along x,

01:16:09.080 --> 01:16:11.950
is a superposition of those two.

01:16:11.950 --> 01:16:15.030
This is a very incredible
physical assumption.

01:16:15.030 --> 01:16:20.310
It's saying this system is a
2-dimensional complex vector

01:16:20.310 --> 01:16:24.850
space, two vectors, two
unit, two basis vectors.

01:16:24.850 --> 01:16:28.860
And from those two, all linear
combinations that are infinite

01:16:28.860 --> 01:16:33.860
represent all possible
spin configurations.

01:16:33.860 --> 01:16:36.090
And what is this saying?

01:16:36.090 --> 01:16:41.060
Well, as we will
translate it into algebra,

01:16:41.060 --> 01:16:45.480
we will say that, look,
here is a state plus.

01:16:45.480 --> 01:16:49.380
And when you try to measure,
if it had any minus component,

01:16:49.380 --> 01:16:50.740
it had nothing.

01:16:50.740 --> 01:16:55.410
So we will state that as
saying that these states are

01:16:55.410 --> 01:16:56.330
orthogonal.

01:16:56.330 --> 01:17:00.590
The minus state and the plus
state have zero overlap.

01:17:03.330 --> 01:17:05.950
They are orthogonal
basis states.

01:17:05.950 --> 01:17:10.910
And, for example, well, you
could also do it this way.

01:17:10.910 --> 01:17:12.800
That would also be 0.

01:17:12.800 --> 01:17:17.540
And you could also
say that z plus

01:17:17.540 --> 01:17:23.370
and z plus is 1, because
every state that came in

01:17:23.370 --> 01:17:26.040
as a plus came out as a plus.

01:17:26.040 --> 01:17:27.910
They had perfect overlap.

01:17:27.910 --> 01:17:32.130
So these are two
orthonormal basis vectors.

01:17:32.130 --> 01:17:34.395
That's what this
seems to suggest.

01:17:34.395 --> 01:17:36.940
And it's a little
strange, if you think,

01:17:36.940 --> 01:17:41.950
because there's a
clash between arrows

01:17:41.950 --> 01:17:45.300
and the notion of
orthonormality.

01:17:45.300 --> 01:17:48.110
In 3-dimensional
vectors, you think

01:17:48.110 --> 01:17:50.489
of this vector being
orthogonal to this.

01:17:50.489 --> 01:17:52.030
But you wouldn't
think of this vector

01:17:52.030 --> 01:17:54.280
as being orthogonal to that one.

01:17:54.280 --> 01:18:00.130
And here is the spin is up,
and this is the spin down.

01:18:00.130 --> 01:18:01.600
And those two are orthogonal.

01:18:01.600 --> 01:18:03.450
You say, no, they're
anti-parallel.

01:18:03.450 --> 01:18:04.780
They're not orthogonal.

01:18:04.780 --> 01:18:06.820
No, they are orthogonal.

01:18:06.820 --> 01:18:12.070
And that's the endlessly
confusing thing about spin-1/2.

01:18:12.070 --> 01:18:16.830
So these states, their pictures
of the spins are arrows.

01:18:16.830 --> 01:18:20.020
But don't think that those
arrows and the dot product

01:18:20.020 --> 01:18:23.370
give you the orthogonality,
because this is up and down.

01:18:23.370 --> 01:18:26.280
If you would be doing the
dot product of an up and down

01:18:26.280 --> 01:18:28.000
vector, you would not get 0.

01:18:28.000 --> 01:18:29.870
But this is 0.

01:18:29.870 --> 01:18:31.860
Then you do the
following experiment.

01:18:36.550 --> 01:18:38.390
So let's do the next one.

01:18:42.820 --> 01:18:47.680
And the next one is,
again, the z filter.

01:18:47.680 --> 01:18:50.920
Take this one, block it.

01:18:50.920 --> 01:18:53.025
Then you put an x filter.

01:18:55.610 --> 01:18:58.550
And what actually happens
is that you would get states

01:18:58.550 --> 01:19:05.570
with Sx, now, h bar over 2 and
Sx equal minus h bar over 2,

01:19:05.570 --> 01:19:07.070
because it's an x filter.

01:19:07.070 --> 01:19:10.490
The magnetic field is a
line in the x direction.

01:19:10.490 --> 01:19:16.630
Now, all these things have
Sz equal h bar over 2.

01:19:16.630 --> 01:19:18.860
And what happens
in the experiment

01:19:18.860 --> 01:19:21.860
is that 50% of the
particles come out here

01:19:21.860 --> 01:19:23.790
and 50% come out there.

01:19:23.790 --> 01:19:29.280
So a spin state
along the x direction

01:19:29.280 --> 01:19:33.340
has some overlap with a spin
state along the z direction.

01:19:33.340 --> 01:19:38.190
Normal vectors, a z vector and
an x vector, are orthogonal.

01:19:38.190 --> 01:19:40.470
Not here for spins.

01:19:40.470 --> 01:19:44.350
The spin pointing in the z
and the spin pointing in the x

01:19:44.350 --> 01:19:46.100
are not orthogonal states.

01:19:46.100 --> 01:19:47.890
They have overlaps.

01:19:47.890 --> 01:19:53.690
So this means that, for example,
the x plus state and the z

01:19:53.690 --> 01:19:58.990
plus state have an overlap.

01:19:58.990 --> 01:20:02.840
This is notations that-- we're
going to be precise later.

01:20:02.840 --> 01:20:11.170
But the same thing with the x
minus state, it has an overlap,

01:20:11.170 --> 01:20:14.140
and somehow they're
about the same.

01:20:14.140 --> 01:20:21.920
Finally, the last experiment
is this, z hat, block again,

01:20:21.920 --> 01:20:26.640
x hat, but this time block one.

01:20:26.640 --> 01:20:32.040
So here is a state with Sx
equals minus h bar over 2.

01:20:32.040 --> 01:20:35.830
Here is a state with
Sz equal h bar over 2.

01:20:35.830 --> 01:20:38.400
And now you put the
z machine again.

01:20:40.980 --> 01:20:44.160
And what happens?

01:20:44.160 --> 01:20:46.330
Well, there's two options.

01:20:46.330 --> 01:20:48.520
People who were inventing
quantum mechanics

01:20:48.520 --> 01:20:50.190
no wonder thought about them.

01:20:50.190 --> 01:20:55.290
Here they could say, look,
I filtered this thing,

01:20:55.290 --> 01:21:01.100
and now all these electrons
have Sz equal h bar over 2.

01:21:01.100 --> 01:21:06.340
And now all these electrons have
Sx equal minus h bar over 2.

01:21:06.340 --> 01:21:08.830
Maybe, actually,
all these electrons

01:21:08.830 --> 01:21:13.420
have both Sz equal
h over 2 and that

01:21:13.420 --> 01:21:15.090
because I filtered it twice.

01:21:15.090 --> 01:21:16.850
So it maybe satisfies both.

01:21:16.850 --> 01:21:20.530
So if all these electrons
would have Sz equals

01:21:20.530 --> 01:21:23.690
h over 2 and this,
then you would only

01:21:23.690 --> 01:21:26.080
get something from the top one.

01:21:26.080 --> 01:21:28.350
But no, that's not what happens.

01:21:28.350 --> 01:21:30.330
You get in both.

01:21:30.330 --> 01:21:36.870
So somehow, the memory of
these states coming from Sz

01:21:36.870 --> 01:21:39.260
equals h over 2
has been destroyed

01:21:39.260 --> 01:21:41.020
by the time it
turned into a state

01:21:41.020 --> 01:21:44.130
with Sx equal minus h over 2.

01:21:44.130 --> 01:21:48.970
And a state cannot have
simultaneously this and that.

01:21:48.970 --> 01:21:54.840
That's two properties, because
you get 50% here and 50% there.

01:21:54.840 --> 01:21:57.760
So we'll discuss next
time a little more

01:21:57.760 --> 01:22:00.500
about these relations
and how can the states

01:22:00.500 --> 01:22:04.480
be related, the ones
that we use as the basis

01:22:04.480 --> 01:22:07.590
vectors and all the
others along x and others

01:22:07.590 --> 01:22:09.790
that we could build
some other way.

01:22:09.790 --> 01:22:10.430
All right.

